The '''Test Assessing Secondary Completion''', or '''TASC''', is a high school equivalency exam. It was chosen by the states of New York and Indiana as a replacement for the [[GED]] exam, effective January 2, 2014.<ref>http://www.acces.nysed.gov/what-hsetasc-test</ref><ref>http://schools.nyc.gov/community/AdultEd/HS_testing/Tasc.htm</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/blog/the_ged_is_out_and_common_core.php?page=all |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-12-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127195800/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/blog/the_ged_is_out_and_common_core.php?page=all |archivedate=2016-01-27 |df= }}</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/03/education/edlife/move-over-ged.html</ref>
The TASC is administered by [[DRC/CTB|Data Recognition Corp.]] and was created by [[McGraw-Hill Education]].<ref>http://www.durangoherald.com/article/20151211/NEWS01/151219898/Colorado-OKs-more-paths-to-obtain-a-diploma</ref>
As of July 2016, the TASC is approved in 13 states. (in the United States).<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/high-school-equivalency-degree-loses-its-dominant-position-1423521427</ref><ref>https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2015/01/09/375440666/a-sizable-decrease-in-those-passing-the-ged</ref><ref>http://www.bighorncountynews.com/editorial/hiset-replaces-ged-montana</ref>
