'''Webster Wells''' (4 September 1851 in [[Boston]] &ndash; 23 May 1916) was a [[United States]] mathematician known primarily for his authorship of a series of mathematical textbooks.
==History== Wells graduated in 1873 at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where he was an instructor from 1873 to 1880, and later became successively an assistant professor (1883), an associate professor (1885), and a full professor (1893-1911) of mathematics.
==Textbooks== Wells' textbooks were used in many schools and colleges in the United States. Among the titles were: * ''Elementary Treatise on Logarithms'' (1878) * ''University Algebra'' (1878) * ''Plane and Spherical Trigonometry'' (1884) * ''Plane and Solid Geometry'' (1887) * ''Higher Algebra'' (1889) * ''College Algebra'' (1890) * ''Academic Arithmetic'' (1893) * ''Complete Trigonometry'' (1900) * ''New High School Algebra'' (1912)
